		<div id="comment-525555">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://kevin-standlee.livejournal.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Kevin</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-525555">
				February 8, 2018 at 11:20					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>The answer I gave regarding television series applies to podcasts as well. If it is a serialized work, then the publication or appearance of the final episode starts the work&#8217;s eligibility clock. If it is a series of stand-along works, each work is eligible on its own based on when it appeared/was published.</p>
<p>If the prose web serial is a single long work released in multiple parts, then it is a single work eligible in 2018 based on its total word count (probably Best Novel based on your description). </p>
<p>If it is a series of stand-alone works, each of which would be eligible on its own, the overall work may be eligible for Best Series if it meets the length requirement (240,000 words).</p>
</div>

				<div class="reply">
